"""
MKT Context Commentary — Ecclesiastes chapters 10–12
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-ecclesiastes-10-12.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/ecclesiastes.json
- data/translation/glossary-hebrew.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/ecclesiastes.json

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch 12's extended allegory of aging (vv1-7) is widely read as a series of body-
  metaphors for the deterioration of old age: the trembling keepers (arms), stooped
  strong men (legs), grinding women (teeth), windows (eyes), street doors (ears), etc.
  The MKT adopts this reading while acknowledging the household/civic reading where
  the images describe a household falling into disrepair is also defensible.
- 12:6 silver cord and golden bowl — the lamp image (bowl/cord) followed by the water
  image (pitcher/wheel at the well): both are images of life-sustaining mechanisms
  that break at death.
- 12:7 "spirit returns to God" — Qohelet is careful not to assert personal immortality;
  the spirit's return to God is the reversal of Gen 2:7 (God breathing life into the
  dust), not a statement about conscious afterlife.
- 12:11 "one Shepherd" — in context, YHWH as the ultimate source of wisdom, not a
  reference to any human teacher. The NT application of this title to Christ is
  secondary (though significant).
- 11:1 "cast bread upon the waters" — most likely refers to maritime commercial
  investment, consistent with the mercantile vocabulary in the book; the agricultural
  "flooding" interpretation is less well-attested in the ANE context.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

ECCLESIASTES = {
  "10": {
    "1": "<p>Dead flies (<em>zevuvei mavet</em>, flies of death/dying) contaminating the perfumer&rsquo;s precious ointment (<em>shemen roqeach</em>) was a recognizable disaster in the ancient Near Eastern economy of luxury goods. Perfumes and aromatic oils were among the most valuable trade commodities of the ancient world — used in royal courts, in religious rites, and in the preparation of the dead. A single dead insect in a sealed jar would set off decomposition processes that rendered the entire expensive preparation worthless. The disproportionate damage of a small cause to a large good makes this image vivid and memorable. The application to wisdom and honor being outweighed by a little folly is the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s warning against the cumulative cost of small moral failures.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The right/left (<em>yamin/semol</em>) orientation of the wise and foolish hearts uses the directional symbolism of the ancient Near East, where right (<em>yamin</em>) was the auspicious direction and left (<em>semol</em>) was inauspicious. This was encoded in physical practice: the right hand was used for blessing and swearing, the left for negative associations. In Hebrew, <em>yamin</em> also means &ldquo;south&rdquo; and <em>semol</em> means &ldquo;north&rdquo; when one faces east (toward sunrise), creating a further correspondence between the auspicious direction (south) and the direction of wisdom. The proverb is not about literal direction but about the orientation — the default tendency — of the wise and foolish person.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The fool&rsquo;s judgment failing while walking — and his showing everyone that he is a fool — reflects the honor-shame culture&rsquo;s assumption that character is visible and public. The fool cannot conceal his inner life because every action and reaction displays it. In the gate-court culture where the community assessed one another through daily interaction, the fool&rsquo;s deficiency was not merely known but continuously demonstrated in even mundane activities. The <em>lev</em> (heart) that &ldquo;fails&rdquo; while walking is the formation-center of the person that has not been shaped by wisdom; its deficiency appears in every context because it is the source of all behavior.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The wisdom of not abandoning one&rsquo;s post (<em>maqomekha</em>, your place) when the ruler&rsquo;s anger flares belongs to the extensive ANE tradition of advice for court officials. Egyptian wisdom texts (the Instruction of Amenemope, the Teaching of Ptah-hotep) devote considerable attention to composure before an angry superior. <em>Marpe'</em> (H4832, composure/calmness/healing — the same root used for the healing word in Prov 12:18) as the response to royal anger is the courtier&rsquo;s skill of de-escalating through steady presence rather than flight or argument. Abandoning one&rsquo;s post in anger compounds the crisis; composure &ldquo;defuses&rdquo; (<em>yanniach</em>, allows to rest) even serious offenses.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The <em>ra'ah</em> (evil/wrong) that proceeds from those in power as a blunder (<em>shegagah</em>, H7684, an unintentional error/mistake) is Qohelet&rsquo;s careful framing of a social criticism: the misallocation of social position is not always intentional wickedness but sometimes the incompetence of those in authority who fail to match people to roles. The <em>shegagah</em> framing (unintentional error) appears in the Pentateuchal law as the category of sin that requires the sin-offering; Qohelet applies it to the structural errors of governance. The entire section (vv5-7) reflects the ANE observation that bad governance produces social inversion.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Fools appointed to high positions (<em>ram</em>, elevated places) and the capable (<em>'ashirim</em>, the wealthy/competent) sitting in lowly positions is the social inversion that the wisdom tradition consistently identified as a sign of systemic disorder. In the ancient Near Eastern political system, the assumption was that positions of authority should be filled by those whose demonstrated competence, family lineage, or royal patronage justified the appointment. The appointment of the <em>kesil</em> (fool, morally insensitive person) to authority was not only personally unfortunate but institutionally catastrophic — the fool&rsquo;s governance would multiply harm throughout the social system.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Servants riding on horseback and princes walking on foot — the reversal of visible status markers — would have been immediately scandalous in the ancient world. Horses were symbols of royal and military power (Deut 17:16 warns the king not to accumulate many horses; 2 Sam 15:1 describes Absalom&rsquo;s chariot and horses as political theater). A servant on horseback while a prince walked on foot inverted every assumed social signal. The observation is Qohelet&rsquo;s documentation of the social chaos that results from the misallocation of authority described in v6: when the wrong people are elevated, the entire system of status-signaling breaks down.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The pit-digging danger (<em>koreh gummatz bo yippol</em>, whoever digs a pit into it may fall) is the ancient trap-and-reversal proverb found across ANE wisdom traditions. It appears in Proverbs 26:27 (pit-digger falls in), Psalm 7:15 (the one who digs a pit falls into it), and Sirach 27:26. The snake in the wall (<em>goredetz gader yishchenu nachash</em>, whoever breaks through a wall, a serpent will bite him) refers to the dry-stone walls common in Palestinian agriculture and construction: snakes nested in the gaps, and demolition work risked disturbing them. Both images describe how dangerous work creates risks beyond the stated task.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The quarrying and splitting hazards are observations about the occupational risks of common labor in the ancient Israelite economy. Quarrying stone (<em>massa' 'avanim</em>) was the foundational work of construction, done with hand tools in exposed conditions; falling stones were an ever-present danger. Wood-splitting (<em>boqa' 'etzim</em>) with an axe involved the unpredictable path of the striking force and the possibility of the blade deflecting. These are not moral observations but practical ones — the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s attention to the physical reality of ordinary work as a dimension of the human condition that Qohelet surveys.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The dull axe requiring greater strength is a practical observation about tool maintenance in the iron-age economy. Iron tools were expensive to produce and required skilled sharpening to maintain their edge; a dull axe (<em>barzel biqheh</em>, iron blunted) required the worker to compensate with force (<em>koach yegarber</em>, strength must increase) for what maintenance would have provided. The application of wisdom (<em>yitron hakhsher chokmah</em>, the advantage of having wisdom succeed) is the principle that preventive intelligence reduces later effort: the wise person maintains their tools, while the fool waits until the situation requires brute force. This is the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s argument for foresight over reactive effort.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The snake charmer who fails to charm before the bite (<em>yekor hannachash belo lachash</em>, if the snake bites before the charming) has gained nothing — and neither has the person who cannot hold their tongue. Snake charming (<em>lachash</em>, H3908, the charm/whispered incantation) was a recognized profession in the ancient Near East; the charmer controlled dangerous animals through trained skill. Applied to the unbridled tongue, the comparison is precise: the tongue-charmer who fails to restrain speech before it strikes has lost the advantage that the skill of restraint was meant to provide. The social damage of the premature word, like the snake bite, cannot be undone by subsequent charming.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The wise person&rsquo;s words earning goodwill (<em>divrei fi-chakham chen</em>, words of a wise person&rsquo;s mouth earn favor/grace) and the fool&rsquo;s words consuming him (<em>sifatot kesil tivalleuennu</em>, the lips of a fool swallow him up) uses the eating/consuming metaphor for speech that is prominent in Proverbs. The social economy of the gate-court where words were the primary currency of relationship-building and dispute-resolution made the quality of one&rsquo;s speech a direct factor in social standing. The wise person&rsquo;s words generate <em>chen</em> (grace/favor, the social goodwill that opens doors); the fool&rsquo;s words generate their own destruction through alienation, enmity, and legal jeopardy.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The fool whose speech begins in folly and ends in wicked madness (<em>'ivvelet</em> beginning and <em>ra'ah holelet</em> ending) traces the trajectory of unchecked foolish speech. The progression from initial foolishness to moral madness in the end reflects the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s understanding that moral character is not static but developmental: the fool whose speech is unchecked becomes more foolish through the practice of foolishness, until the endpoint is not merely silliness but dangerous madness. This is the inverse of the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s account of how wisdom grows through the practice of receiving and applying instruction.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The fool multiplying words (<em>yarbeh devarim</em>, increases words) while knowing nothing about the future — and yet speaking as if he does — is the social phenomenon of the person whose verbal confidence exceeds their epistemic standing. In the ANE wisdom tradition, the wise person was precisely the one who knew what they knew and what they did not know: the willingness to say &ldquo;I do not know&rdquo; was a mark of wisdom, not weakness. The fool&rsquo;s multiplied words often function as a cover for this ignorance — verbal volume compensating for actual knowledge. Qohelet&rsquo;s repeated emphasis on the unknowability of the future makes the fool&rsquo;s confident speech about it an ironic self-condemnation.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The fool&rsquo;s labor exhausting all around them and their inability to find their way to the city — the standard social reference point of the ancient world — is the image of comprehensive social and geographic incompetence. The city (<em>qiryah</em>, the walled urban center) was the destination of commercial, legal, and social activity; not knowing how to get to the city was the proverbial limit of practical incompetence. The exhaustion the fool causes in others reflects the real social cost of relying on the incompetent: those who depend on fools must expend additional energy compensating for failures of judgment and execution.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The woe to the land whose king is a child (<em>na'ar</em>, boy/youth/inexperienced person) and whose rulers carouse in the morning (<em>baboqer yoshelu</em>, feast in the morning) draws on the widespread ANE association between the age/maturity of a ruler and the quality of their governance. Morning feasting was the sign of the ruler who could not restrain appetite — the self-indulgent leader who prioritized pleasure over duty. The connection is political-ethical: the ruler who cannot govern his own schedule and appetite will not be able to govern the state. <em>Na'ar</em> here may refer not to literal youth but to the immaturity of character that marks poor leadership regardless of age (cf. Isaiah&rsquo;s use of the same social critique).</p>",
    "17": "<p>The blessed land whose king is of noble birth (<em>ben-chorim</em>, son of free men/nobles) and whose princes eat for strength and not excess (<em>bigvurah ve-lo' basheti</em>, for strength and not for drinking) presents the positive ideal: rulers whose character has been shaped by the disciplines of their station. The phrase <em>ben-chorim</em> (son of free men) has a dual resonance: the nobility of birth that theoretically guaranteed quality formation, and the nobility of character that demonstrated itself in restraint. Eating &ldquo;for strength&rdquo; is the disciplined consumption that fuels productive work rather than the self-indulgent consumption that depletes it.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The rafters sagging and the house leaking through great laziness (<em>be'atzelatayim yimokh hamiqreh</em>, through great sloth the ceiling sinks) is the domestic architecture observation that applies to political leadership. The house in ancient Palestine was a functional unit requiring constant maintenance: the flat-roofed stone and timber construction of the period needed regular attention to its structural elements. The laziness that allows the roof to sag and leak is the same laziness that allows governance to deteriorate. Qohelet uses the domestic metaphor to make the political point: a government, like a house, requires active maintenance. Neglect produces structural failure with the same certainty as it does in construction.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The feast prepared for enjoyment and wine that gladdens life placed alongside money that &ldquo;provides for everything&rdquo; (<em>ha-kesef ya'aneh 'et-hakkol</em>, money answers/provides for everything) is Qohelet&rsquo;s realistic observation about the instrumental value of money. The phrase is often misread as endorsing materialism; the context is the description of royal excess in vv16-17 and the response of the rulers who feast instead of govern. The observation is sardonic: yes, money does provide for everything — feasts, wine, pleasure — but this is precisely the problem with rulers who prioritize it. The observation functions as a critique of the governance-by-consumption that vv16-17 describe.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The warning against cursing the king even in private thought and the wealthy even in the bedroom — because a bird may carry the words — draws on the widespread ANE belief and experience that private speech has a way of reaching its targets. The phrase entered popular usage: the proverb &ldquo;a little bird told me&rdquo; derives from this verse. In the ancient world, where palace informants, household servants, and community surveillance were constant realities, the counsel to guard even private speech was practical, not merely spiritual. The <em>ba'al kenafayim</em> (the master of wings, the winged creature) carrying the report is the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s acknowledgment that no speech is truly private in a community where everyone&rsquo;s affairs are eventually known.</p>"
  },
  "11": {
    "1": "<p>Casting bread upon the waters (<em>shelach lachmecha 'al-penei hamayim</em>, send your bread on the face of the waters) most likely refers to maritime commercial investment — the practice of shipping grain and goods by sea in the hope of profitable return. The ancient Near Eastern trade routes that ran through Palestinian ports (Joppa, Dor, Caesarea) connected the grain surplus of Egypt and Mesopotamia to the markets of the Mediterranean world; the speculative investment of grain capital in maritime trade was a recognized economic activity. The return &ldquo;after many days&rdquo; (<em>ki berov hayamim timtza'ennu</em>) describes the typical lag of maritime trade rather than miraculous provision. The counsel is one of generous risk-taking in the face of uncertainty.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The instruction to give a share to seven, even to eight (<em>ten-cheleq leshiv'ah ve-gam lishmonah</em>) uses the graduated-number formula common in Hebrew and ANE poetry: seven-then-eight means &ldquo;all and more&rdquo; (cf. Amos 1-2: &ldquo;for three transgressions and for four&rdquo;; Mic 5:5: &ldquo;seven shepherds and eight princes&rdquo;). The widest possible distribution of generosity is the counsel, grounded in the wisdom that calamity is unpredictable: distributing one&rsquo;s investments and generosity broadly means that when some ventures fail, others survive. This is the ancient wisdom of portfolio diversification applied to social generosity — spreading one&rsquo;s investment in human relationships and charitable giving as the preparation for uncertain futures.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The clouds that fill with rain pouring it on the earth and the fallen tree lying where it falls — both are observations about natural inevitability that have no reversibility. The rain falls when the clouds are full; this cannot be prevented or redirected by the observer. The tree lies where it falls; the direction of its fall is determined by the conditions at the moment and cannot be corrected afterward. Both images are preparations for the counsel of vv4-6: act despite not being able to control outcomes. The fallen tree lying wherever it falls became, in later rabbinic literature, an image of death: one dies in the state of character one has achieved, with no posthumous correction possible.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The person who watches the wind will never sow; the cloud-watcher will never reap — the Palestinian agricultural calendar was governed by wind and weather in ways that required both attention and risk. The <em>ruach</em> (wind/spirit) that the sower monitors for optimal sowing conditions and the clouds that the reaper monitors for harvest timing are real constraints on agricultural planning. But the farmer who waits for perfect conditions will never act: the Palestinian growing season is too short and the weather too variable for the luxury of perfect timing. The wisdom is not to ignore conditions but to act within imperfect conditions — a practical epistemology of decision-making under uncertainty that applies broadly beyond agriculture.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The unknowability of the wind&rsquo;s path and the formation of bones in the womb place divine mystery at the center of the practical wisdom counsel. The formation of bones (<em>atzamim</em>) in the pregnant woman&rsquo;s womb was one of the most awe-inspiring mysteries of the ancient world: the development of the infant from conception to birth was entirely hidden from observation. Psalm 139:13-15 celebrates this same mystery (&ldquo;you knitted me together in my mother&rsquo;s womb&rdquo;; &ldquo;fearfully and wonderfully made&rdquo;). Qohelet cites it as the positive limit of human knowledge: just as we cannot understand the work of God in the womb, we cannot fully understand it in any of its operations — which is the reason to act without waiting for full comprehension.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Sowing in the morning and not resting the hand in the evening — double-shift sowing — is the agricultural application of the generosity-principle of v2: since we do not know which effort will succeed (the morning sowing or the evening), we should do both. The Palestinian growing season allowed for multiple sowing windows depending on the crop and the rainfall; the diligent farmer who used all available opportunities was more likely to succeed than the one who sowed only at the &ldquo;optimal&rdquo; time. This is the practical complement to the counsel against cloud-watching in v4: do not wait for perfect conditions, and do not stop at the first opportunity — use every available window for productive effort.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Light being sweet and the goodness of seeing the sun (<em>ve-tov la'einayim lirot 'et-hashemesh</em>) — the simple, sensory appreciation of continued life — functions as the joy-framework for the counsel that follows. The light and the sun are the primary symbols of life and presence in the ancient world: to see the sun is to be among the living, as opposed to the darkness of Sheol. The sweetness of light is the experiential ground for Qohelet&rsquo;s repeated counsel to embrace the gift of the present day. The wisdom tradition&rsquo;s affirmation of sensory existence as a gift — not something to be fled from but received — is expressed in its most elemental form here.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The instruction to rejoice through all one&rsquo;s years while remembering that the days of darkness will be many — and that all that comes is vapor (<em>hevel</em>) — frames the joy-counsel in the context of mortality. The &ldquo;days of darkness&rdquo; (<em>yemei hachoshekh</em>) most naturally refers to Sheol, the realm of the dead — described consistently in the Hebrew Bible as darkness, silence, and forgetfulness (Ps 88:12; 143:3; Job 17:13). The many days of Sheol are set against the few bright days of life: the imbalance between the short present and the long future of darkness is the intensification of Qohelet&rsquo;s recurring theme about the urgency of present enjoyment. <em>Hevel</em> (vapor) at the end of the verse is the universal category that even the joy-counsel exists within.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The address to the young man (<em>bachur</em>) to rejoice in his youth, follow the desires of his heart, while knowing that God will bring all things into judgment combines the positive counsel (enjoy youth fully) with the covenantal frame (divine judgment for all things). This combination is unusual in the wisdom tradition and has been debated: is &ldquo;know this — God will bring you into judgment&rdquo; a later scribal addition, or is it genuinely Qohelet&rsquo;s own counterweight? The consensus view is that Qohelet himself holds both poles: the genuine goodness of youth and desire alongside the genuine reality of divine accountability. The young man who enjoys his youth in forgetfulness of judgment is enjoying it wrongly; the one who enjoys it in full awareness of judgment is enjoying it rightly.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The instruction to banish (<em>haser</em>, remove) anxiety from the heart and pain from the body — for childhood and youth are vapor (<em>hashachrut hevel</em>, the dawn/youth is vapor) — completes the youth address with the temporal frame. <em>Hevel</em> applied to youth makes the urgency explicit: the window for carefree enjoyment closes. <em>Ka'as</em> (H3708, vexation/anxiety) and <em>ra'ah</em> (pain/evil) are the two internal states that premature aging of the spirit produces; the counsel to remove them is not denial of reality but the wisdom of not letting worry colonize the present. The application of <em>hevel</em> to youth — the most apparently permanent and vital state — is Qohelet&rsquo;s sharpest use of the vapor-metaphor for temporal things.</p>"
  },
  "12": {
    "1": "<p>The instruction to remember one&rsquo;s Creator (<em>zechor 'et-bor'echa</em>) in the days of youth (<em>bimei bechurotekha</em>), before the days of trouble arrive, sets the entire extended allegory of aging that follows within the framework of covenantal remembrance. <em>Zakar</em> (H2142, to remember) in the Hebrew Bible is not merely a cognitive act but a covenantal one — to remember YHWH is to orient oneself toward him in loyalty and practice. The &ldquo;days of trouble&rdquo; (<em>yemei hara'ah</em>) and the years when there will be no pleasure are the years of physical decline described in the poem that follows; the time to establish the relationship with the Creator is before those years arrive, while the capacity for active response remains.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The darkening of sun, light, moon, and stars and the clouds returning after the rain — the introductory elements of the allegory — use the imagery of failing light for the diminishing senses and vitality of old age. The Palestinian experience of the dark winter season, when clouds returned repeatedly after short breaks of sunshine, was the image of the final years: not a complete darkness all at once but the repeated failing and partial return of light without the full brightness of youth. The sun, moon, and stars as the three great lights of the created order represent the full range of sensory and cognitive vitality; their darkening maps onto the comprehensive diminishment of old age.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The allegory proceeds through the imagery of a household in decline: the keepers of the house (<em>shomerei habayit</em>) trembling are most likely the arms and hands — the body&rsquo;s protective, grasping functions — shaking with age. The strong men stooping (<em>anshei hachayil</em>) are the legs that no longer support upright carriage. The grinding women stopping because they are too few (<em>hatovenot ki mi'etu</em>) are the teeth, whose reduction in number affects the grinding of food. Those looking through the windows growing dim (<em>haro'ot ba'arubot vachashekhu</em>) are the eyes, whose visual acuity decreases with age. The household is the body; its staff and functions are the body&rsquo;s capacities; their deterioration is the deterioration of age.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The street doors being shut (<em>nisgereu daltayim bashuk</em>) represents the closing off of social engagement — the ears that no longer catch the sounds of street life clearly. The sound of grinding fading low (<em>bish-fal qol hatichanah</em>) completes the tooth-grinding image of v3: fewer teeth, softer sounds. Waking at the mere chirp of a bird (<em>yaqum leqol hatzippor</em>) — the light sleeping of the elderly that is disturbed by the smallest sound — and the voices of song brought low (<em>yishsapelu kol-habbanot hashir</em>) — the diminished ability to hear music — complete the sensory picture of the aging person who is increasingly isolated from the auditory world that once connected them to the community.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Fear of heights and dread on every path (<em>miyigva'ot yira'u ve-chatatchatiim baderekh</em>) describes the combination of physical fearfulness and generalized anxiety that accompanies old age: the confident movement of youth replaced by caution and dread. The almond tree blossoming (<em>yanotz hashaqed</em>) — the almond is the first tree to blossom in the Palestinian spring, its white flowers appearing before its leaves — is an image of white hair that appears before the other signs of age. The grasshopper becoming a burden (<em>vistaggel hechagav</em>) is the once-trivial weight that now becomes oppressive to the weakened body. Desire failing (<em>vataper ha'aviyyonah</em>, the caper/desire-fruit perishes) is the loss of appetite and vitality. The mourners already walking the streets is the community&rsquo;s anticipation of the death that is imminent.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The silver cord and golden bowl (<em>chevel hakesef&hellip; gullat hazzahav</em>) are an alternative image of life as a lamp: the golden bowl (the lamp-vessel containing oil) suspended by a silver cord (the mechanism of suspension), which when severed drops the bowl, shattering it and extinguishing the lamp. The second pair — the pitcher at the spring and the wheel at the well (<em>kad 'al-hamabbua'&hellip; haggalgal 'el-habor</em>) — completes the water-provision images: the vessel that carries life-sustaining water and the wheel-mechanism that draws it from the well. When the pitcher breaks at the spring and the wheel breaks at the well, the water of life can no longer be drawn. Both images convey the fragility of the mechanism of life and the finality of its breaking.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The return of dust to earth (<em>ve-yashuv he'afar 'al-ha'aretz kishehayah</em>) reverses the creation-act of Genesis 2:7: God formed man from the dust of the ground (<em>'afar min-ha'adamah</em>). Qohelet&rsquo;s observation is not theological speculation about afterlife but a precise reversal of the creation narrative: the dust that was animated by God&rsquo;s breath (<em>nishemat chayyim</em>) returns to its pre-animated state. The spirit returning to God who gave it (<em>haruach tashuv 'el-ha'elohim asher netanah</em>) is the corresponding reversal of the divine act of endowment: what God gave as life-breath he receives back. Qohelet does not use this as the basis for a doctrine of personal immortality; it is the observation that the human person is constituted by a divine gift that is returned.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The repetition of the book&rsquo;s opening declaration — <em>havel havalim amar haQohelet hakkol havel</em> (vapor of vapors, says the Teacher — all is vapor) — serves as the formal bracket that closes the autobiographical section of the book (begun at 1:2). The return of the same declaration at the end of the extended meditation on aging and death is not mere rhetorical symmetry but the conclusive demonstration of the thesis: having surveyed wisdom, pleasure, wealth, labor, justice, and the entire human project &ldquo;under the sun,&rdquo; the Preacher finds the diagnosis confirmed. <em>Hevel havalim</em> (vapor of vapors, the superlative form) at the close of the poem on death is the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s most concentrated statement of mortality&rsquo;s pervasiveness.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The epilogue shifts from first-person reflection to third-person description of the Teacher and his method. The description of Qohelet as having listened carefully (<em>ve'izzen ve-chiqer tiqen meshalim harbeh</em>, he listened/weighed and investigated and arranged many proverbs) outlines the three stages of the wisdom teacher&rsquo;s work: reception (<em>'izzun</em>), investigation (<em>chaqar</em>), and arrangement (<em>tiqen</em>). This is the ANE scribal methodology — the careful weighing of received wisdom, its critical investigation, and its artful organization into memorable form. The Qohelet&rsquo;s description of his own method mirrors the Hezekiah scribes of Proverbs 25:1 and the broader scribal activity of the royal court that preserved, edited, and arranged the wisdom of Israel.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The Teacher seeking to find pleasing words (<em>divrei chefetz</em>, words of delight/pleasure) and writing honestly (<em>ve-katuv yosher divrei 'emet</em>, what was written was honest — words of truth) establishes the dual standard of wisdom literature: aesthetic appeal and truthfulness. The two are not in tension in the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s understanding: the pleasing word that is not true is flattery; the true word that is not pleasing is harsh. The ideal is the word that is both truthful and artfully shaped — Proverbs&rsquo; golden apples in silver settings (Prov 25:11). <em>'Emet</em> (truth/faithfulness) as the standard for Qohelet&rsquo;s writing grounds the book&rsquo;s unsettling honesty about the limits of wisdom as a deliberate truth-commitment, not mere skepticism.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The words of the wise as goads (<em>darbanot</em>, H1861, the pointed stick used to drive cattle) and firmly driven nails (<em>masmerot netu'im</em>) given by one Shepherd (<em>me'ro'eh echad</em>) frames wisdom as both painful and permanent. The goad that drives the ox is not gentle but purposeful — it produces movement that would not otherwise happen. The firmly driven nail holds what it fastens permanently. Both images emphasize that genuine wisdom operates on the person through productive discomfort and lasting effect. The one Shepherd (<em>ro'eh echad</em>) from whom all wisdom proceeds is most naturally YHWH, the Shepherd of Israel (Ps 23; 80:1) — wisdom&rsquo;s ultimate source is divine speech and guidance rather than merely accumulated human observation.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The warning against endless book-making (<em>'asot sefarim harbeh ein qetz</em>, the making of many books has no end) reflects the ANE scribal culture&rsquo;s productive excess. The royal libraries of Nineveh, Ugarit, and Egypt contained vast accumulations of texts — medical, legal, religious, wisdom, administrative — and the scribal profession&rsquo;s output was seemingly inexhaustible. Qohelet&rsquo;s counsel is not anti-intellectual but prioritizing: if even the wisest compilation of wisdom (this book) ends in <em>hevel</em>, then the infinite accumulation of books adds only weight without resolution. <em>Yagi'at basar</em> (weariness of the body) as the cost of much study is the physical reality of the ancient scholar whose work of copying, memorizing, and disputing was genuinely laborious.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The concluding formula <em>sof dabar hakkol nishma'</em> (the conclusion of the whole matter, when all is heard) introduces the covenantal synthesis: fear God and keep his commandments, for this is the <em>kol-ha'adam</em> (the whole of every person). The return to the covenant vocabulary at the close of a wisdom book that has consistently explored the limits of wisdom <em>under the sun</em> is the book&rsquo;s fundamental move: wisdom that operates without the fear of YHWH (the beginning of wisdom, Prov 1:7) arrives at <em>hevel</em>; wisdom that is grounded in the covenant arrives at the comprehensive human vocation. <em>Yir'at 'elohim</em> (fear of God) and <em>shemor mitzvotav</em> (keep his commandments) are the vocabulary of the covenant relationship that the wisdom of Proverbs and Deuteronomy share.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The final verse — God bringing every act into judgment, including every hidden thing (<em>kol-ma'aseh ha'elohim mishpat 'al kol-ne'alam</em>), whether good or evil — completes the covenantal framework that v13 introduces. The divine judgment that encompasses the hidden (<em>ne'alam</em>, what is concealed, what cannot be observed by the human community) is the answer to the entire series of injustices and perversities that Qohelet has observed under the sun: the wicked buried while the righteous perish (8:14), the race not going to the swift (9:11), the fool appointed to authority (10:6). None of these escapes the final divine account. The book that has consistently acknowledged what human wisdom cannot resolve ends by asserting the divine judgment that will resolve what wisdom cannot see through.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'ecclesiastes')
    merge_comm(existing, ECCLESIASTES)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'ecclesiastes', existing)
    total = sum(len(vv) for vv in ECCLESIASTES.values())
    parts = ', '.join(f'ch{ch}={len(ECCLESIASTES[ch])}' for ch in sorted(ECCLESIASTES, key=int))
    print(f'Ecclesiastes 10-12 mkt-context: {total} verses written ({parts}).')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
